Mail Merge with Thunderbird

Thunderbird is a mail client that is available on Windows, Mac, and Linux. Despite a humdrum user interface, one of Thunderbird's great strengths is its customizability.

  • Download Thunderbird here

Extensions

There are literally dozens, if not hundreds, of extensions you can add to Thunderbird to extend its capabilities. Two that are very useful are:

  • Mail Merge P - for sending a batch of customized emails to a list

  • HTML Source Editor - allows you to customize the HTML in an outgoing email

Overview

To do a mail merge, you will need two things:

  1. a data file you create outside of Thunderbird (commonly via spreadsheet)

  2. a template email you create within Thunderbird

Creating a Data File

You can use whatever field names (variable names) you want in Mail Merge, but for our purposes we use: First, Last, Email. The easiest way to prepare a data file is to create a spreadsheet with these field names as column headers:

When you have your spreadsheet ready, export the data to a comma delimited text file with the file extension "csv". This will be the file you use for the mail merge:

Creating the Template Email

Open up Thunderbird and create a new email. Where you would enter a person's first and last names or email address you instead will use the variable names surrounded by double-curly brackets:

xxxxxxxxxx
{{First}} {{Last}} {{Email}}

In the TO: field in the email type:

{{First}} {{Last}} <{{Email}}> **[and hit enter]**

Don't worry if it appears to generate an error. That's because it's the pattern of an email, not a real email address. You may use the same variables in the Subject and the Body of the email as long as you use the double-curly brackets. For example:

Before you actually send out the emails, one feature of Thunderbird very useful for doing mailings to the media is the ability to generate Return Receipts and Delivery Status Notifications. Was the email delivered? Did someone open and read it? You'll receive individual notices for each mail sent.

When you are ready to proceed, click on the "Mail Merge" icon at the top right (see arrow). This brings you to an empty mail merge page where you will be asked to locate the names and emails for use with your email:

Click on the file icon (arrow above) to add your data. You will then see an operating system dialog box for choosing your data file. In this case, we will choose the "test.csv" file created earlier:

When you have verified the names and email addresses are the ones you want, click on "Next" to proceed:

Before you hit the "Send" button you have the ability to scroll through the emails that the Mail Merge extension wil be sending out. Notice how the double-curly bracketed variables have been replaced with the data from the text file.

Sending

There is a slight delay between each email that you send. If you have a long list, be patient. If the email provider's SMTP (mail transfer) service is slow, you may see a warning message or even a prompt to resend a message. If this happens you don't need to re-send the entire list; just respond to the prompt to send the one email that was having trouble.

Tip

Put your own name and email address in the list at the end. That way you can be confident the mailing worked and you can see exactly what the other recipients received.
